{"id":"2204.12032","submitter":"Kei Suzuki","authors":"Katsumasa Nakayama and Kei Suzuki","title":"Remnants of nonrelativistic Casimir effect on the lattice","comments":"5 pages, 4 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph cond-mat.mes-hall hep-lat hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The Casimir effect is a fundamental quantum phenomenon induced by the\nzero-point energy for a particle. It is well-known for relativistic particles\nwith a linear dispersion relation, while its existence or absence for\nnonrelativistic particles with a quadratic dispersion is an unsettled question.\nHere, we investigate the Casimir effects for various dispersion relations on\nthe lattice. We find that Casimir effects for dispersions proportional to an\neven power of momentum are absent in a long distance but a remnant of the\nCasimir effect survives in a short distance. Such a remnant Casimir effect will\nbe experimentally observed in materials with lattice degrees of freedom, such\nas thin films, narrow nanoribbons, and short nanowires. In terms of this\neffect, we also give a reinterpretation of the Casimir effect for massive\nparticles.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 26 Apr 2022 02:06:30 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-04-27"}
{"id":"2204.12033","submitter":"Li Chen","authors":"Guozhong Zheng, Jiqiang Zhang, Zhenwei Ding, Lin Ma, and Li Chen","title":"Pinning control of social fairness in the Ultimatum game","comments":"13 pages, 6 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1088/1742-5468/accf07","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.soc-ph cond-mat.stat-mech q-bio.PE","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Decent social fairness is highly desired both for socio-economic activities\nand individuals, as it is one of the cornerstones of our social welfare and\nsustainability. How to effectively promote the level of fairness thus becomes a\nsignificant issue to be addressed. Here, by adopting a pinning control\nprocedure, we find that when a very small fraction of individuals are pinned to\nbe fair players in the Ultimatum Game, the whole population unexpectedly\nevolves into the full fairness level. The basic observations are quite robust\nin homogeneous networks, but the converging time as a function of the pinning\nnumber shows different laws for different underlying topologies. For\nheterogeneous networks, this leverage effect is even more pronounced that one\nhub node is sufficient for the aim, and a periodic on-off control procedure can\nbe applied to further save the control cost. Intermittent failures are seen\nwhen the pinning control is marginally strong, our statistical analysis\nindicates some sort of criticality. Our work suggests that the pinning control\nprocedure could potentially be a good strategy to promote the social fairness\nfor some real scenarios when necessary.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 26 Apr 2022 02:08:01 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 4 Jan 2023 06:42:49 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-05-10"}
